WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:01:19.330 --> 00:01:20.400
GITA WIRJAWAN: Hello, friends, 

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:24.550
today we have with us
 Dr. Tirta Mandira Hudhi. 

00:01:24.550 --> 00:01:26.480
Tirta, thank you so much for coming. 

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:29.370
TIRTA MANDIRA HUDHI: I’m honored 
to be invited, Mr. Gita.

00:01:29.370 --> 00:01:33.840
I usually just watch your lectures online, 
but now I get to be here in person.

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:39.750
You're a very smart guy. Tell us what it 
was like growing up in Solo

00:01:40.420 --> 00:01:46.460
your background, so people can understand 

00:01:46.460 --> 00:01:53.240
how you became such a reader and 
how you developed your thinking.    

00:01:53.840 --> 00:01:58.420
One privilege I used to deny,

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:03.240
I used to deny it. Back in 2014,

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:05.310
I would always say I came from nothing.

00:02:05.310 --> 00:02:10.800
But I started accepting the truth 
around 2021, 2022.   

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:13.840
And my biggest privilege 
was education. 

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:17.770
My parents were both educators. 

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:23.440
My dad was an economics lecturer
 at a university in Indonesia.  

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:30.710
But due to income needs, he had to 
pivot for financial reasons 

00:02:30.710 --> 00:02:34.440
he left his job after 9 years 

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:39.840
and became a banker at a 
rural bank in Central Java.   

00:02:40.280 --> 00:02:43.040
My dad is a native Javanese,
 from Sambi, Boyolali. 

00:02:43.280 --> 00:02:46.350
Our family name is Wongsodimejo. 

00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:48.950
His name is Sutarjo,
you can check, it’s real.   

00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:53.370
Another privilege. in 1998, 
my dad was invited 

00:02:53.370 --> 00:02:57.930
by President Habibie to a meeting 
as an economic expert 

00:02:57.930 --> 00:02:59.950
to discuss the financial crisis.   

00:02:59.950 --> 00:03:03.510
He was that serious 
about math and finance. 

00:03:03.510 --> 00:03:05.910
That’s something I never 
really shared before,

00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:06.970
but there’s a photo.   

00:03:07.420 --> 00:03:10.800
My mom, on the other hand, 
studied agricultural science. 

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:14.020
She’s of Chinese descent, from 
Wotgandul in Semarang. 

00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:17.710
She graduated cum laude
 in agriculture from UNS.   

00:03:18.280 --> 00:03:23.330
She used to be a teaching assistant, but because 
her younger siblings needed financial support, 

00:03:23.330 --> 00:03:26.330
she switched careers and became
 a banker. Imagine that.   

00:03:26.330 --> 00:03:31.510
From science to banking. Back in elementary 
and middle school, I thought that was normal. 

00:03:31.510 --> 00:03:35.350
But in high school, once science and 
social studies were separated

00:03:35.350 --> 00:03:38.020
I realized it wasn’t.  So, yeah, she graduated in agriculture,

00:03:38.480 --> 00:03:41.530
actual agriculture, not agricultural 
technology, from UNS, 

00:03:41.530 --> 00:03:44.660
and ended up in banking.   

00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:49.110
Both my parents were born in 1958 

00:03:49.110 --> 00:03:51.260
and met at a library. 

00:03:52.280 --> 00:03:54.220
So they were both book lovers.   

00:03:54.220 --> 00:03:55.110
-Which city? 

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:55.910
-Surakarta.

00:03:55.910 --> 00:03:58.710
They met in college and 
eventually had me. 

00:03:58.710 --> 00:04:04.080
They only wanted one child.  

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:06.150
Because my dad calculated it-

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:06.770
-Barely enough? 

00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:07.460
-Yes,

00:04:07.970 --> 00:04:11.570
They were middle-class. Not poor, 
not rich—right in the middle.   

00:04:12.150 --> 00:04:17.130
My dad was the second child, 
my mom the eldest. 

00:04:17.130 --> 00:04:20.530
My dad’s Muslim, my mom’s Catholic. 

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:25.020
And I don’t know— don’t want to know,

00:04:25.020 --> 00:04:30.170
I don't know how they got married. That’s their business.   

00:04:30.170 --> 00:04:33.200
So yeah, that’s my privilege. 

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:37.930
My dad had an entire room just 
for books—a full library.   

00:04:37.930 --> 00:04:44.770
Back in elementary school, he once
 gave me a thesis to read.   

00:04:45.080 --> 00:04:47.000
That’s where my reading habit started. 

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.730
My dad began talking to me seriously 
when I was in first grade.   

00:04:50.730 --> 00:04:53.750
He always said, 

00:04:53.750 --> 00:04:58.840
“I’m a middle-class guy. I sent you to a 
Catholic school, Kanisius Keprabon 2,

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:01.930
where your classmates are all from 
rich families, kids of entrepreneurs.

00:05:01.930 --> 00:05:03.930
I can’t afford tutoring until 
you’re in third grade, 

00:05:03.930 --> 00:05:06.110
so the only thing you can 
do is study hard. 

00:05:06.110 --> 00:05:08.840
What brings pride to our family 
is your academic success.”   

00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:12.730
That’s what he told me. 
You can ask him directly,

00:05:12.730 --> 00:05:15.400
he’s still working, still a banker,
 refuses to retire.  

00:05:15.400 --> 00:05:18.130
He says retiring would 
make him senile. 

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:20.730
His words. And that kind of 
talk shaped me to believe

00:05:20.730 --> 00:05:26.130
that academics were everything

00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:29.420
that it was the way to bring
 honor to the family.  

00:05:29.420 --> 00:05:32.350
I was raised like that from first grade. 

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:36.930
I ranked 9th at first—then 9th, 7th, 6th.   

00:05:36.930 --> 00:05:40.840
By second grade I started understanding, 

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:44.400
and I begged my mom for a tutor. 

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:49.660
Eventually they gave in and got
 me one tutor—for math. 

00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:55.550
By second grade I ranked 2nd. From third grade 
until high school, I was always ranked 1st.  

00:05:57.060 --> 00:05:59.640
A big reason for that was 

00:06:00.550 --> 00:06:02.950
being able to go to my parents’ workplaces.   

00:06:03.620 --> 00:06:07.840
Since we were middle-class 
and couldn’t afford a maid, 

00:06:08.350 --> 00:06:11.820
after school I was picked up by a 
pedicab driver named Mr. Nuri.   

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:14.930
I still remember everyone who helped me, 
his name was Mr. Nuri. 

00:06:14.930 --> 00:06:20.410
Shoutout to him. He’d take me 
to my mom’s office at Pasar Legi.   

00:06:20.410 --> 00:06:26.010
My mom was a banker at a small branch
 of a private bank in Pasar Gede.   

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:30.170
That’s where I’d do homework 
and math exercises,

00:06:30.170 --> 00:06:33.570
hang out with her coworkers, 
and observe what she did.   

00:06:33.570 --> 00:06:38.860
So yeah, companies that allow employees 

00:06:38.860 --> 00:06:41.950
to bring their kids to work end
 up raising kids like me.   

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:44.220
Shoutout to those kinds of directors. 

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:47.530
My mom’s boss allowed it.

00:06:47.530 --> 00:06:48.880
 “It’s okay, bring your child.”   

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:52.730
So I’d spend about three hours in 
that office—from 1 PM to 4 PM. 

00:06:52.730 --> 00:06:56.130
After that, I went to tutoring,
 then headed home.

00:06:56.130 --> 00:07:00.350
I was fully independent from 
second to fifth grade.   

00:07:00.350 --> 00:07:02.440
My parents gave me clear goals. 

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:04.950
I didn’t even own a Tamagotchi.   

00:07:04.950 --> 00:07:08.460
If I wanted a PlayStation 1, 
I had to hit a certain rank.   

00:07:08.950 --> 00:07:12.530
My dad never broke his promises.

00:07:12.530 --> 00:07:15.600
He always said, “These goals aren’t for me, 
they’re for you."

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:19.480
"If you’re not smart, you won’t
 get into college. 

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:24.640
And the only way to lift our family’s dignity 
is through academic achievement.”   

00:07:24.640 --> 00:07:25.950
And I internalized that.   

00:07:26.130 --> 00:07:30.370
By fifth grade, I was representing my
 school as a model student.   

00:07:30.370 --> 00:07:34.570
Back in elementary, there were contests like the 
Olympiads and model student competitions.   

00:07:34.570 --> 00:07:37.020
Since I was ranked 1st from grade 4 to 5,

00:07:38.110 --> 00:07:42.880
We only switched to semesters in grade 5. I was
 born in 1991, and before that, we had trimesters.   

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:46.080
Anyway, I entered the model
 student competition.   

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:48.860
I still remember—I had two teachers:
 Mrs. Ati and Mr. Suryo.   

00:07:48.860 --> 00:07:50.880
Mr. Suryo was the math teacher.  

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:53.660
I never forget my teachers.  

00:07:54.420 --> 00:07:57.260
I ended up 3rd place in the city.   

00:07:57.260 --> 00:08:02.330
1st place was from SD 15, 2nd from SD 16, 
those were the famous schools in Surakarta.  

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:05.140
3rd place was me, from SD Kanisius.   

00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:09.440
At that time, I really believed that being 
smart would get me scholarships.   

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:14.950
Dunkin Donuts used to give free 
donuts to the top 3 students.  

00:08:14.950 --> 00:08:16.780
No joke. I loved that program.  

00:08:16.780 --> 00:08:17.710
- Sugar rush.   

00:08:17.710 --> 00:08:21.860
-I didn’t realize that at the time, 
I was just a kid.   

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:25.780
Because I stayed in the top 3 
from grades 1 to 6, 

00:08:25.780 --> 00:08:29.860
I got a one-year scholarship to Pangudi Luhur 
Bintang Laut for junior high.   

00:08:31.110 --> 00:08:34.260
That school’s on Slamet Riyadi.   

00:08:34.260 --> 00:08:43.040
In 7th grade, I ranked 1st again.   

00:08:43.040 --> 00:08:47.510
-I also went to Pangudi Luhur for
 junior high, in Jakarta, Haji Nawi.   

00:08:47.510 --> 00:08:49.580
-Ah, then you’re familiar.   

00:08:49.580 --> 00:08:53.840
In 8th grade, I ranked 1st again. 
So yeah, during that early phase,

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:57.290
Hope it’s okay I’m going into detail. 
Don’t want netizens to get the wrong idea.   

00:08:57.580 --> 00:09:00.330
In that early phase, my parents 

00:09:00.330 --> 00:09:03.290
gave me clear academic targets 
starting at age 7.   

00:09:05.090 --> 00:09:09.020
But there was a downside, 
which I’ll get into later.   

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:11.710
In junior high, I could still handle it.   

00:09:11.710 --> 00:09:17.690
In 8th grade, I joined three Olympiads,

00:09:17.690 --> 00:09:23.000
math, science, and English.   

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:28.330
Thanks to those, I was offered a
 scholarship to Saint Joseph College.   

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:33.800
I passed, but didn’t go, living
 expenses were too high.   

00:09:33.800 --> 00:09:39.890
I also got a scholarship to Regina Pacis, a year 
later at the Ursuline school in Solo.   

00:09:39.890 --> 00:09:43.840
There, I kept ranking 1st, 

00:09:44.460 --> 00:09:46.860
and eventually made it into the 
top science class, IPA 1.  

00:09:46.860 --> 00:09:51.040
I didn’t join the international standard school (RSBI)—
it didn’t exist for my generation. 

00:09:51.040 --> 00:09:52.600
RSBI came after me.   

00:09:52.600 --> 00:09:56.800
That’s when the conflict with 
my parents started.   

00:09:57.260 --> 00:10:01.730
The downside of all those targets hit 
in high school, I was burned out.   

00:10:01.730 --> 00:10:06.690
I rebelled. I hated it.   

00:10:06.690 --> 00:10:10.800
I felt like I was studying just 
to please my parents.   

00:10:11.350 --> 00:10:14.840
So I acted out.   

00:10:14.840 --> 00:10:17.820
Got in trouble. I still remember 
my principal, Sister Floren.

00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:19.890
She called my parents in all the time.  

00:10:19.890 --> 00:10:22.550
So there I was, in the top class, academically
 gifted but with a bad attitude.   

00:10:22.980 --> 00:10:26.110
Always in trouble, fighting with teachers, 
fighting with classmates, 

00:10:26.110 --> 00:10:30.820
constantly getting called in.   

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:33.980
Until one day, my dad had
 a serious talk with me.   

00:10:33.980 --> 00:10:39.660
He said, “It’s up to you. Whatever you 
want to be, that’s your choice.”   

00:10:39.980 --> 00:10:43.150
Then I ran away from home 
to a friend’s place.   

00:10:43.150 --> 00:10:46.490
And what did my friend do?
 Took me to Gramedia.   

00:10:46.490 --> 00:10:48.950
So dumb, honestly. Sorry, Mr. Gita.   

00:10:48.950 --> 00:10:52.530
He took me to Gramedia, and
 that’s where I read a book 

00:10:52.530 --> 00:10:54.400
called A Child Called ‘It’.

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:57.350
The author was Dave Pelzer.  
 I still remember the author.   

00:10:57.350 --> 00:10:58.530
There were three books.   

00:10:58.530 --> 00:11:02.530
In the third one, I read about this kid 
who was abused by his mom,   

00:11:02.530 --> 00:11:06.750
then in the second book, he survived, and 
in the third, he forgave her. It was wild.   

00:11:06.750 --> 00:11:10.840
You can read the book by Dave Pelzer, 
A Child Called It. It’s a trilogy.  

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:14.180
In the third book, he becomes a 
pilot and forgives his mom.   

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:17.660
Because yeah, she was still his mom.   

00:11:17.660 --> 00:11:21.710
That’s when I started to realize that the 
reason my parents set targets for me   

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:24.950
was for my own good, not theirs.  

00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:28.620
 In 9th grade, I joined Ganesha 
Operation (a tutoring center).  

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:32.540
That was my first time doing tutoring 
and meeting kids from public schools.  

00:11:33.420 --> 00:11:35.280
That’s when my point of
 view started to shift.  

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:38.620
Turns out they were really open-minded,   

00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:41.820
and they were surprised,   
“Why are you in tutoring?”  

00:11:41.820 --> 00:11:44.420
“Aren’t Chinese kids in Solo 
usually not into tutoring?”   

00:11:44.420 --> 00:11:47.000
That’s what they actually said, 
it was hilarious.   

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.550
The GO center was in Kota Barat.   

00:11:50.040 --> 00:11:56.330
I joined because I was curious, 
what’s the national exam really like?   

00:11:57.200 --> 00:11:59.730
Eventually, I chose the GO 
class that made me think,   

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:04.640
“Okay, maybe I do want to 
go to a public university.”   

00:12:06.910 --> 00:12:11.936
There was a three-way debate. My dad 
went to UNS, my mom went to UNS.   

00:12:11.936 --> 00:12:15.970
They were worried about me going to 
a public university because I’m Chinese.   

00:12:15.970 --> 00:12:20.110
I argued with my dad, “Dad, you’re indigenous
 and you got married just fine.”   

00:12:20.110 --> 00:12:23.060
He went silent.   
Sorry, Dad.   

00:12:23.060 --> 00:12:25.220
That was the first time I talked 
back, and my dad didn’t get mad.   

00:12:25.700 --> 00:12:28.480
“Okay, if you want to go to a public
 university, it has to be a good one.”   

00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:28.930
Okay. 

00:12:29.230 --> 00:12:31.920
So I set a goal, my first choice was the med school at Undip.   

00:12:32.430 --> 00:12:33.230
-Masya Allah.

00:12:33.230 --> 00:12:35.980
-Undip med school, but not through,   

00:12:35.980 --> 00:12:37.120
-Why medicine?   

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:38.940
-Because my mom’s from Semarang.   

00:12:40.540 --> 00:12:41.580
-But why medicine specifically?

00:12:43.250 --> 00:12:47.050
-Because I wanted to aim high. In SNMPTN 
or other entrance exams,   

00:12:47.050 --> 00:12:50.100
medicine always had the highest cutoff.   

00:12:50.100 --> 00:12:50.980
-Cool.   

00:12:51.630 --> 00:12:54.470
-My ego was through the roof. 
I needed validation.   

00:12:55.320 --> 00:13:02.320
As an only child whose life revolved around
 academics, I constantly needed such validation.   

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:04.780
-Did that come from within,   

00:13:04.780 --> 00:13:08.410
or was it more about the 
culture at home?  

00:13:08.410 --> 00:13:12.940
 -More the family culture. My dad and 
mom always drilled into me   

00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:14.360
-That you had to be the best?  

00:13:14.360 --> 00:13:19.010
-Always the best, because only 
then would people respect you.   

00:13:19.010 --> 00:13:21.810
That was one of our family values.   

00:13:21.810 --> 00:13:23.650
-More from your dad or your mom?   

00:13:24.070 --> 00:13:27.450
-For academics, definitely my dad. 
He was all about that.   

00:13:27.450 --> 00:13:31.520
My mom was more like, “It’s okay,” 
laid-back, accepting.  

00:13:31.520 --> 00:13:34.340
But my dad was strict. 
“If you’re not the best,   

00:13:34.340 --> 00:13:36.700
you’re wasting your potential.   

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:38.920
You’ve got a brain , use it.   

00:13:38.920 --> 00:13:41.100
You’re my only child, so you’ve 
got to be the best.”   

00:13:41.100 --> 00:13:43.940
At the very least, if not academically,
 then in something else.   

00:13:44.630 --> 00:13:48.300
So I was like, “Alright, I’ll be the best,” 
and that brainwashing

00:13:48.300 --> 00:13:51.450
 led me to pick medicine.   

00:13:51.700 --> 00:13:55.160
I applied to three places: 
Undip, UGM, ITB.   

00:13:55.160 --> 00:13:57.210
Electrical engineering was the hardest.  

00:13:57.210 --> 00:14:00.960
I got accepted into Undip, not through SNMPTN, 
but through the independent exam,   

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:05.520
which had 120 Olympic-level questions. 
I was at fourth place, and I got in.   

00:14:05.780 --> 00:14:11.050
We found out from my mom’s friend, who turned 
out to be a professor of agriculture at Undip.   

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:13.160
He let us know I got accepted, 
and I was thrilled.  

00:14:15.630 --> 00:14:19.270
Meanwhile, my school Ursulin 
had no connection with UGM.   

00:14:19.270 --> 00:14:21.850
So I had to submit the documents 
to UGM myself.   

00:14:22.250 --> 00:14:26.960
In public schools, they have a B2B channel   

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:34.500
where students submit their documents 
together through the school.    

00:14:34.500 --> 00:14:37.450
But since Ursulin didn’t have that 
kind of access to UGM,   

00:14:37.450 --> 00:14:39.450
I had to carry the documents around myself.  

00:14:39.450 --> 00:14:44.030
I wanted UGM not because it was 
better, no, it was the buildings.   

00:14:44.670 --> 00:14:46.960
The Radiopoetro building, 
I still remember it.   

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:51.230
I went there for a math Olympiad
 in 12th grade,   

00:14:51.230 --> 00:14:53.050
my last competition in the first semester.  

00:14:53.050 --> 00:14:56.700
I was blown away by UGM’s campus.  

00:14:57.340 --> 00:14:59.940
I chose Undip med school because
 my mom’s from Semarang.   

00:14:59.940 --> 00:15:04.670
But I applied to UGM because I had 
that Olympiad there. I didn’t win.  

00:15:04.670 --> 00:15:08.210
I lost to a kid from Padmanaba, 
SMA 3 Jogja. Badly.   

00:15:08.210 --> 00:15:09.810
I was ranked 6th, he was 2nd.   

00:15:09.810 --> 00:15:11.450
Didn’t make it to the provincial level.   

00:15:11.450 --> 00:15:13.230
I still remember, math Olympiad.   

00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:14.810
I lost by two questions. So frustrating.   

00:15:14.810 --> 00:15:16.810
But the building was awesome.   

00:15:16.810 --> 00:15:19.670
So I thought, “Wow, this place is cool,
 Radiopoetro, just like this.”   

00:15:19.940 --> 00:15:25.560
And in the end, I applied and got into UGM.   

00:15:25.560 --> 00:15:30.180
But I wasn’t satisfied, I also applied to 
Undip med school and to ITB.   

00:15:30.180 --> 00:15:32.520
I wanted to test myself.  

00:15:32.520 --> 00:15:34.520
I also got accepted to seven private universities.   

00:15:35.250 --> 00:15:37.270
Flexing. My ego was still huge.   

00:15:37.630 --> 00:15:39.810
Getting into med school was the 
third big turning point in my life,  

00:15:40.140 --> 00:15:45.520
because once I was there, I realized there were 
way more smart people than I expected.  

00:15:45.520 --> 00:15:49.870
I met kids from Insan Cendekia,   
they were next level smart.   

00:15:49.870 --> 00:15:52.670
The Incen kids. And the TN kids.  

00:15:52.980 --> 00:15:56.010
They had those cropped haircuts.  
The girls had short hair,   

00:15:56.010 --> 00:15:58.010
and they were insanely smart.  

00:15:58.360 --> 00:16:01.520
I used to think Tirta was the only one,   

00:16:01.520 --> 00:16:04.980
Young Tirta with a 4.0 GPA 
until the 4th semester.   

00:16:04.980 --> 00:16:10.540
Nope. 60% of FK students had all A’s
 for four semesters at UGM.   

00:16:10.540 --> 00:16:14.250
And the most intense competition,
 I can name the top five schools.  

00:16:14.250 --> 00:16:14.920
-Masya Allah.

00:16:14.920 --> 00:16:20.450
-TN, Incen, SMA 8 Jakarta,
 3 Semarang, 3 Jogja.   

00:16:20.450 --> 00:16:25.700
Then the ones who would stir 
things up in class discussions,    

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:33.120
3 Bandung, then 70 Jakarta,   

00:16:33.120 --> 00:16:43.050
Labschool Rawamangun, 1 Teladan, and another
 one I forgot, I think from Surabaya.   

00:16:43.050 --> 00:16:49.430
So the culture in public universities 
completely changed me.   

00:16:50.410 --> 00:16:56.580
Before, my parents set the expectations.   

00:16:56.580 --> 00:17:02.610
I finished high school thinking smart
 people always succeed.  

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:06.900
Because like I said earlier, my 
dad brainwashed me 

00:17:06.900 --> 00:17:10.720
to believe that smart people 
always win in life,

00:17:10.720 --> 00:17:15.760
so I had to be smart to raise
 my quality of life.  

00:17:16.180 --> 00:17:18.410
Then I’d be successful.  

00:17:18.410 --> 00:17:24.070
And in high school, “success” meant
 a lot of money and such. 

00:17:24.670 --> 00:17:28.630
But in med school, there were just so 
many smart people, and I hit a reality check:   

00:17:29.430 --> 00:17:31.010
doctors don’t make money right away.   

00:17:31.010 --> 00:17:35.410
3.5 years of theory, now it’s 4 years by regulation.   

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:38.976
2 years of clinical work, 1 year of internship,
 then 2 years of work, 

00:17:38.970 --> 00:17:41.216
5 years for specialization, 
that’s 14 years total.   

00:17:41.270 --> 00:17:42.030
-Wow.

00:17:42.430 --> 00:17:47.050
-In semester 3, I hit a wall.   

00:17:47.050 --> 00:17:51.580
So mentally, honestly, even before Gen Z was
 talking about it, I was already burned out.  

00:17:51.760 --> 00:17:57.100
“This is bad.” That’s when I started to be more 
realistic, having talks like this with my parents.   

00:17:57.100 --> 00:18:04.500
The third core value in our family. 
First, academics. Second, having goals,   

00:18:04.500 --> 00:18:05.630
always being goal-oriented.   

00:18:05.630 --> 00:18:07.430
Third was openness.  

00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:09.630
We’d have three-way discussions every month.

00:18:11.870 --> 00:18:13.230
I’d speak honestly,   

00:18:13.450 --> 00:18:19.720
“Dad’s 50, Mom’s 50, in 
five years you’ll retire.   

00:18:21.030 --> 00:18:25.700
Your pension could end up paying for my specialization,
 which costs 15 million per semester.

00:18:25.700 --> 00:18:29.700
No income for five years. I’m their only child, 
and that’s assuming I succeed.   

00:18:30.050 --> 00:18:34.210
If I don’t earn my own money, our 
family finances could collapse.”   

00:18:35.540 --> 00:18:36.270
-Wow.

00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:41.700
-That’s when I got real. I learned to 
be realistic in med school.   

00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:45.580
And then I made a big decision.   

00:18:45.580 --> 00:18:51.030
In semester 2, I started selling 
stuff on Kaskus.  

00:18:51.560 --> 00:18:56.340
I sold Power Balance, Blackberries, 
and it worked.   

00:18:56.870 --> 00:19:00.520
Sorry, they were illegal Blackberries,
 I sold those back then.   

00:19:00.520 --> 00:19:04.250
Got them from a reseller, 
packaged them myself,   

00:19:04.250 --> 00:19:06.650
and used the money to save up for tuition.   

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:11.940
UGM tuition was cheap, just 2.2 million 
per semester. I still remember.   

00:19:11.940 --> 00:19:15.520
It wasn’t a legal entity yet back then,
 so it was still subsidized.   

00:19:15.520 --> 00:19:18.500
So I paid the 2.2 million myself,
 even my rent.   

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:20.340
My parents only gave me pocket money.   

00:19:20.340 --> 00:19:23.210
Eventually, by semester 5, I was 
covering everything on my own.  

00:19:23.670 --> 00:19:30.520
Young guy, 4.0 GPA, earning his 
own money. My ego was massive.   

00:19:31.380 --> 00:19:32.096
Then it got crushed. 

00:19:32.096 --> 00:19:34.090
I applied four times to be a teaching 
assistant and got rejected every time.   

00:19:34.500 --> 00:19:40.180
Biochem, rejected. Pathology anatomy, 
rejected. Anatomy, rejected.   

00:19:40.180 --> 00:19:42.410
Totally crushed. My ego was shattered again.   

00:19:42.410 --> 00:19:47.340
What always crushed my ego was
 being around smart people.   

00:19:47.340 --> 00:19:52.430
When I’m around less smart people, 
my ego gets huge , every time.   

00:19:52.430 --> 00:19:56.540
And eventually, with all that,
 I realized I’m an only child.   

00:19:56.540 --> 00:19:59.030
I had to make money.   

00:20:00.760 --> 00:20:04.230
I dove into retail.   

00:20:04.980 --> 00:20:07.340
Selling shoes, dealing with people.   

00:20:07.340 --> 00:20:11.320
And then I met my professors. And again,
 it was teachers who changed me.   

00:20:11.320 --> 00:20:13.500
I met three of them:   

00:20:13.500 --> 00:20:15.850
The late Prof. Iwan , he contributed 
a lot during COVID.   

00:20:15.850 --> 00:20:20.210
He also helped get Novomix 
covered by BPJS, I think.   

00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:29.470
Second was Dr. Denny , he’s a professor 
of physiology at UGM.   

00:20:30.010 --> 00:20:33.410
Third was Dr. Gofir, a neurologist.   

00:20:34.270 --> 00:20:37.470
All three told me the same thing:   
“You’ve worked in sales,   

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:40.520
you’ve done retail, met lots of people.   

00:20:41.300 --> 00:20:46.140
Doctors take care of patients, 
so who takes care of doctors?”   

00:20:46.140 --> 00:20:50.780
That hit me. Because to doctors, the
 coolest thing is holding a scalpel.   

00:20:51.650 --> 00:20:56.500
I loved emergency cases.
 I loved general surgery,   

00:20:56.500 --> 00:20:57.900
digestive surgery, orthopedics,  

00:20:57.900 --> 00:21:02.810
anything involving a scalpel, 
I loved the adrenaline.   

00:21:02.810 --> 00:21:08.050
And for doctors, holding a scalpel is the 
sexiest thing. Like, seriously cool.   

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:15.340
But all three professors told me 
to go into management. 

00:21:17.650 --> 00:21:24.230
That made me think. I graduated with 
a 3.8 GPA. Internship. Loved the ER.   

00:21:24.670 --> 00:21:30.320
After finishing my internship in 2016,  
someone gave me advice,  

00:21:32.010 --> 00:21:35.140
and I made the biggest decision, 
 to bury my dream, man.   

00:21:35.670 --> 00:21:40.850
The dream of becoming an orthopedic surgeon,
 a surgeon in general, I buried it in 2016.   

00:21:42.180 --> 00:21:46.120
Because I saw my dad aging   

00:21:46.120 --> 00:21:50.780
and I asked him seriously, like if 
Mr. Gita here were my dad ,   

00:21:50.780 --> 00:21:54.580
and I’m the kind of guy who 
can’t sugarcoat things,   

00:21:54.580 --> 00:21:57.900
I asked, “Dad, if your savings are 
used for my specialization,   

00:21:59.160 --> 00:22:03.180
does that mean you and Mom 
won’t get to enjoy retirement?”

00:22:03.180 --> 00:22:04.070
No. 

00:22:05.470 --> 00:22:08.720
Then I said, "I can earn money now, 
my life is settled here. 

00:22:09.180 --> 00:22:14.160
Why don’t you just spend the money 

00:22:14.900 --> 00:22:19.250
to visit countries you’ve never been to, 
because you deserve that. 

00:22:21.500 --> 00:22:22.920
I’ll make my own money." 

00:22:23.360 --> 00:22:32.410
At first, they couldn’t accept it. We didn’t argue, 
but it was my mom who accepted it. 

00:22:32.870 --> 00:22:34.270
So I got my mom’s blessing. 

00:22:34.270 --> 00:22:38.340
"It’s okay if you’re happy earning money, 
that’s fine. I’ll talk to your dad." 

00:22:38.340 --> 00:22:43.920
So in 2016, I started practicing
 until 2017. 

00:22:44.360 --> 00:22:47.470
In 2017, I buried my dream of becoming 
a practicing doctor.

00:22:48.210 --> 00:22:51.340
Because I realized that if I stayed selfish
 about pursuing specialization,

00:22:51.780 --> 00:22:56.500
I wouldn’t give my dad who was already 
58 the chance to enjoy his life. 

00:22:57.810 --> 00:23:01.870
My dad was 58 at that time, 
nearing 60, already retired. 

00:23:01.870 --> 00:23:05.160
If I used up his savings for my specialization 
and specialists don’t get paid, you know  

00:23:05.160 --> 00:23:09.470
I’d become a specialist, but my dad would 
never get to go abroad in his whole life.

00:23:10.300 --> 00:23:12.430
He once tried to get a scholarship, 

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:15.940
I don’t know what it was called back then, 
but his TOEFL score was only 200. 

00:23:15.940 --> 00:23:19.140
My dad couldn’t speak English. Bad. 
Super thick accent.

00:23:19.140 --> 00:23:22.450
Even worse than mine. 
His simple past tense was terrible. 

00:23:22.900 --> 00:23:25.050
He never traveled abroad in his life. 

00:23:25.500 --> 00:23:28.030
The first time my dad ever went 
overseas was when he was 60.

00:23:31.580 --> 00:23:35.780
If I had been selfish about my specialization,
 I would’ve become one, 

00:23:35.780 --> 00:23:38.650
but my dad would never have traveled. 

00:23:38.980 --> 00:23:43.230
I had to be realistic. I’m not a 
sandwich generation, 

00:23:43.230 --> 00:23:46.270
but they’re already elderly, 

00:23:46.270 --> 00:23:51.920
and they’ve never even seen another 
country in their whole lives? 

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:56.960
My dad still doesn’t dare go on a hajj pilgrimage
 because he’s afraid the money will run out.

00:23:57.450 --> 00:24:01.740
In the end, I’m the one paying for it 
hopefully this year, if not next year. 

00:24:01.740 --> 00:24:03.050
After convincing him.  

00:24:03.050 --> 00:24:06.470
-But at the time, did it never cross your mind to 
look for a scholarship or something like that?   

00:24:06.470 --> 00:24:09.320
-No, because I was embarrassed 
by my friends. 

00:24:09.320 --> 00:24:10.500
I had three friends. 

00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:13.850
In med school, that’s where my ego got hit the 
most. Med school changed everything. 

00:24:13.850 --> 00:24:17.010
Getting into a state university changed me. 
I met someone named Dr. Sunardi, sir. 

00:24:17.500 --> 00:24:22.780
You could invite him here. 
Dr. Sunardi’s dad was a gravekeeper. 

00:24:23.610 --> 00:24:26.100
He has a PhD though. 

00:24:27.050 --> 00:24:31.920
He came from a poor background. 
Got all his scholarships. 

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:35.780
To make ends meet, he used to 
summarize lectures, 

00:24:36.180 --> 00:24:39.780
then sell the summaries in a magazine. 

00:24:39.780 --> 00:24:42.210
Summaries. He sold them to other students 

00:24:42.210 --> 00:24:45.830
so they didn’t have to print slides 
 just read the summaries he made. 

00:24:46.740 --> 00:24:52.650
He graduated late because he joined research 
projects so he could keep getting paid. 

00:24:54.070 --> 00:24:56.030
I met a lot of people whose 

00:24:56.030 --> 00:24:59.160
parents were worse off than mine. 

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:04.670
I’d feel ashamed to take a scholarship
 while my friends  

00:25:04.670 --> 00:25:08.580
well, it’s like this: my parents could still afford 
things, and I could still earn money. 

00:25:08.580 --> 00:25:12.010
But my friends’ parents were 
in worse shape financially.

00:25:12.010 --> 00:25:14.580
If I forced my ego at that time,

00:25:14.580 --> 00:25:17.320
 I’d feel like I was taking someone else’s 
opportunity. That was a dilemma for me. 

00:25:17.320 --> 00:25:20.450
So I decided, I think I can still 
make it on my own. 

00:25:20.450 --> 00:25:22.080
Earn my own money. 

00:25:22.080 --> 00:25:26.060
That’s why I never dared to take 
a scholarship, even until now. 

00:25:26.750 --> 00:25:30.240
Because I still feel,
“I can still afford it myself.”  

00:25:30.240 --> 00:25:33.990
So because I was making money, I buried my 
dream and focused on managing people. 

00:25:36.470 --> 00:25:38.960
When I turned 25, that was 
my fourth big change.

00:25:39.710 --> 00:25:43.880
I got famous. 

00:25:43.920 --> 00:25:45.670
Something I never imagined. 

00:25:45.670 --> 00:25:49.056
By the time I was 26, I started getting
 invited to seminars in Jogja 

00:25:49.056 --> 00:25:51.050
because my shoe cleaning business
 was booming. 

00:25:51.310 --> 00:25:55.240
And I was a doctor, so I got 
invited to universities. 

00:25:55.240 --> 00:26:00.420
My Instagram hit 100,000 followers.
 Instagram became active in 2013, 

00:26:00.420 --> 00:26:04.400
and I started personal branding in 2017. 
My ego was high. 

00:26:05.110 --> 00:26:10.790
By 2020, I became the “dr. Tirta” that Mr. Gita knows, 
all is wrong in my eyes. 

00:26:11.580 --> 00:26:12.980
Why did I think everyone was wrong? 

00:26:12.980 --> 00:26:17.020
Maybe netizens or even Mr. Gita,
 hearing me ramble, would think, 

00:26:17.020 --> 00:26:20.180
“Oh this kid’s never really 
struggled in life.” True. 

00:26:20.180 --> 00:26:24.310
I was used to being number one. I was 
always number one. I was an only child. 

00:26:24.310 --> 00:26:29.120
I got into med school easily, could earn money, I could sell. 

00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:37.350
But I got hit hard because of fame and my inability 
to take advice from people on social media. 

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:42.040
In 2020, I think back now, and that version 
of Dr. Tirta was really arrogant. 

00:26:42.760 --> 00:26:45.670
And I only realized it because
 of a life event.

00:26:46.400 --> 00:26:51.880
I was cycling far, met someone who helped me,
 I gave him money and he threw the money.

00:26:51.880 --> 00:26:54.500
“Not everything is about money, bro.

00:26:54.500 --> 00:26:57.540
I helped you because we’re on the same road. 

00:26:57.540 --> 00:26:59.550
Your bike is more expensive than my truck,

00:26:59.550 --> 00:27:02.160
but what good is it on the road?” 
I went silent. 

00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:05.060
That happened twice in Indramayu.  

00:27:05.800 --> 00:27:09.580
Hit me hard. While riding from Indramayu
 to Simpang Jomin, I thought, 

00:27:11.020 --> 00:27:12.720
“Man, I’ve been such an idiot all this time.” 

00:27:12.720 --> 00:27:16.980
I changed because I met a truck 
driver whose name I still don’t know  

00:27:16.980 --> 00:27:18.300
helped me for 50 kilometers. 

00:27:18.300 --> 00:27:22.200
He said he helped me because 
he thought I was a ghost.

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:24.960
I was cycling, he lit me up from behind 
with his headlights. 

00:27:25.550 --> 00:27:29.070
Then he said, “I’ll keep the lights on for 
50 kilometers, my house is ahead,

00:27:29.670 --> 00:27:31.820
but don’t give me money. 
I don’t need your money. 

00:27:31.820 --> 00:27:34.190
We’re on the same road, 
we should help each other.”

00:27:34.190 --> 00:27:35.340
I still remember his words, 

00:27:35.340 --> 00:27:38.820
“People who live on the road 
must help each other.” 

00:27:40.440 --> 00:27:44.440
That shattered me. Cracked my ego. 

00:27:44.840 --> 00:27:50.000
When I got home, I still remember, it was March 2022, 
I immediately registered for ITB. 

00:27:50.760 --> 00:27:53.400
Something I never liked, management.

00:27:53.640 --> 00:27:56.340
I needed acceptance, sir. 

00:27:56.510 --> 00:28:00.420
My lecturers, the late Prof. Iwan, 
dr. Gofir, and dr. Denny  

00:28:00.420 --> 00:28:03.960
had been asking me to focus on 
managing people since 2016. 

00:28:03.960 --> 00:28:10.340
I didn’t listen to them for six years, 
and it takes me 6 years to finish the study. 

00:28:10.880 --> 00:28:14.540
At ITB, I met more brilliant people. 

00:28:14.540 --> 00:28:20.000
I met two generations at once, mentors
 like Bu Nila, Bu Yuni Ros, Pak Yos. 

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.350
I’m the type of person who
 always looks up to mentors. 

00:28:22.350 --> 00:28:25.180
And I met Gen Zs who are just 
unbelievably smart. 

00:28:25.300 --> 00:28:28.070
Some were 24 and already had a
 master’s degree. Like, how? 

00:28:28.070 --> 00:28:32.760
Their GPA in undergrad was 3.9, and I asked, 
“Why do you want to get a master’s?”

00:28:32.760 --> 00:28:34.630
“Because I still feel dumb at work.” 

00:28:36.310 --> 00:28:38.760
“You’ve only worked a year and you already 
feel dumb and go back to school?”

00:28:38.760 --> 00:28:40.600
“Yeah, my dad can afford it.” 

00:28:42.260 --> 00:28:47.560
There I was, meeting two different 
generations. I changed again, I evolved. 

00:28:48.020 --> 00:28:53.580
Turns out smart people never stop reading, 
even after getting degrees. 

00:28:53.580 --> 00:28:57.190
The difference between smart and 
intelligent people is  

00:28:57.550 --> 00:29:02.040
if someone thinks they’ve made it because
 they have a degree and they stop reading,

00:29:02.040 --> 00:29:03.510
that’s where their knowledge stops.  

00:29:04.150 --> 00:29:07.390
My mentors were willing to listen to me. 

00:29:08.120 --> 00:29:11.510
They saw me as a resource.

00:29:11.960 --> 00:29:14.480
 I was shocked. I was still in 
my master’s program. 

00:29:14.750 --> 00:29:18.600
That’s when I realized  oh, this is what separates 
people who go on to do a PhD. 

00:29:18.600 --> 00:29:20.600
I still remember my lecturer, 
her name’s Bu Nila. 

00:29:20.960 --> 00:29:27.080
She’s amazing. Same age as me,
 already a PhD by 27. 

00:29:27.080 --> 00:29:30.560
She said to me, “Tirta, don’t get cocky, okay?
 I’m gonna show off, Tirta. 

00:29:30.560 --> 00:29:34.980
Come on guys, Tirta is 31, 
owns a store, right? 

00:29:34.980 --> 00:29:37.700
I got my PhD at 27. 
Where were you at 27, Tirta?” 

00:29:37.700 --> 00:29:38.950
Oof, I surrendered. 

00:29:39.280 --> 00:29:45.760
They teased me, but I loved it because 
there were people smarter than me. 

00:29:45.760 --> 00:29:49.230
And smart people always explain 
things so clearly. 

00:29:49.520 --> 00:29:53.240
Thanks to Bu Nila, I became super 
focused on data. 

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:56.500
I don’t want to say anything I don’t fully 
understand anymore. 

00:29:56.700 --> 00:29:59.360
Because of her, I now only focus 
on three things: 

00:29:59.820 --> 00:30:05.500
health, knowledge, and business 
&amp; marketing strategic analysis  

00:30:05.500 --> 00:30:07.500
because I really love those fields.  

00:30:07.500 --> 00:30:13.070
From Bu Yuni Ros, who taught HR, 

00:30:13.070 --> 00:30:18.340
She instilled in me the idea 

00:30:19.320 --> 00:30:23.420
that if you stop learning, 
your career is over. 

00:30:25.220 --> 00:30:26.670
Knowledge is everything. 

00:30:27.100 --> 00:30:29.980
Sure, you’re a doctor, but if 
you learn this well, 

00:30:29.980 --> 00:30:32.280
you can get two things. 

00:30:32.510 --> 00:30:37.220
In healthcare, you have the foundation, 
but every doctor manages patients  

00:30:37.220 --> 00:30:39.750
you can manage the doctors. 
That hit me hard. 

00:30:39.750 --> 00:30:42.940
Finally, from Pak Yos  he said to me, 

00:30:43.840 --> 00:30:47.960
“Money spent on education is not 
an expense, it’s an investment.” 

00:30:49.580 --> 00:30:52.790
I graduated from ITB with a GPA of 3.9. 

00:30:53.580 --> 00:30:58.830
I was supposed to give the graduation speech 
as the most inspiring graduate. 

00:30:58.830 --> 00:31:05.110
I still remember, it was Pak Yos who chose me 

00:31:05.110 --> 00:31:12.780
to speak at Hotel Intercontinental Bandung. 

00:31:14.310 --> 00:31:15.460
But I didn’t want to speak, sir. 

00:31:16.270 --> 00:31:19.400
Because I told him, there's still someone-

00:31:19.400 --> 00:31:22.230
Here’s where my ego finally softened 

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:26.470
“Tirta, you’re speaking, you’ll represent the graduates.” 
The reason I refused was... 

00:31:26.470 --> 00:31:30.720
I have the chat history where I declined 
to represent the graduates. 

00:31:31.030 --> 00:31:36.440
Because I felt there was someone 
smarter than me, his name is Nelson. 

00:31:37.380 --> 00:31:41.470
He spoke seven languages, 
had a GPA of 3.99, sir. 

00:31:42.840 --> 00:31:44.560
At ITB

00:31:44.560 --> 00:31:48.270
I felt he was more worthy than me
 to represent the students. 

00:31:49.040 --> 00:31:49.800
And they accepted that.

00:31:50.680 --> 00:31:55.950
So from that long story I’ll sum 
it up into five things.   

00:31:56.320 --> 00:31:58.350
My parents instilled the importance 
of setting targets,   

00:31:58.990 --> 00:32:03.500
that without knowledge, you won’t 
understand the world.   

00:32:04.030 --> 00:32:08.460
And knowledge can elevate your status, that’s true, 
but it doesn’t guarantee success.

00:32:09.350 --> 00:32:12.980
In high school I learned to 
control my ego.   

00:32:13.640 --> 00:32:18.800
I hit rock bottom, fought with my parents, came 
to understand that the targets they gave me  

00:32:19.180 --> 00:32:23.700
were actually targets meant for myself, and  
 in high school I felt arrogant.   

00:32:23.700 --> 00:32:29.360
In college I realized that 
reality doesn’t align with   

00:32:29.360 --> 00:32:33.800
what my parents had taught me, that  
 knowledge is indeed important   

00:32:33.800 --> 00:32:36.780
but it doesn’t guarantee you’ll 
be 100% successful.   

00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:39.430
Because you don’t have the same privileges  
 as your other friends.   

00:32:39.430 --> 00:32:42.060
You’re an only child, you can’t choose 
where you’re born.   

00:32:42.060 --> 00:32:47.580
So you have to sacrifice your dreams 
for something bigger.   

00:32:49.460 --> 00:32:53.990
During the pandemic I learned 
 about popularity.   

00:32:54.470 --> 00:32:57.840
Turns out, smart and successful people   

00:32:57.880 --> 00:33:00.550
who can’t control their egos
 will fall apart.   

00:33:00.920 --> 00:33:06.460
And their egos will lose to people who 
 may not be academically smart,   

00:33:06.460 --> 00:33:09.470
but through experience, they’re 
more important.   

00:33:10.110 --> 00:33:11.780
So this fourth lesson I really learned.  

00:33:11.780 --> 00:33:17.830
We can learn not only from smart people, 
not only from the wealthy.   

00:33:17.830 --> 00:33:23.180
We can also learn from people who 
may be below us financially,   

00:33:23.180 --> 00:33:25.510
but above us in terms of wisdom.   

00:33:25.510 --> 00:33:29.430
That was the fourth thing I learned, from 
 a truck driver who gave me a lecture.   

00:33:29.710 --> 00:33:33.590
At ITB I learned that life-long learning  
 is everything.   

00:33:33.590 --> 00:33:35.060
Which brings us back to number one.   

00:33:36.100 --> 00:33:38.240
So these five phases shaped 
who I am now   

00:33:38.240 --> 00:33:41.510
and maybe at 40 I’ll learn 
something new.  

00:33:41.510 --> 00:33:43.190
It’s from these things that I believe

00:33:44.320 --> 00:33:49.430
Without my parents, there wouldn’t 
 be the version of me today,   

00:33:49.640 --> 00:33:52.040
because my parents burdened me  
 with targets.   

00:33:52.430 --> 00:33:56.240
Without my rebellious self in high school  
 I wouldn’t be who I am today.   

00:33:56.240 --> 00:34:00.440
Because I knew my ego was huge in high school, 
I was a rebel, defiant, opposed everything.   

00:34:01.200 --> 00:34:08.220
Without my professors at FK UGM,  
 I wouldn’t have learned how to face reality.   

00:34:09.320 --> 00:34:12.280
Without the life event 
 that happened while cycling,   

00:34:12.900 --> 00:34:15.120
my ego wouldn’t have crumbled 
 for the second time.   

00:34:15.120 --> 00:34:18.390
So my ego fell twice, once in high 
school, and recently.   

00:34:18.390 --> 00:34:22.030
Without my teacher at ITB I wouldn’t 
understand books.   

00:34:22.880 --> 00:34:25.350
And maybe there will be other life events.   

00:34:25.350 --> 00:34:29.220
This is the culture that I think 
exists in my family.   

00:34:30.020 --> 00:34:33.160
Open to knowledge.   

00:34:33.160 --> 00:34:43.300
Knowledge can come from books, professors, other 
experiences, self experiences, articles, papers.   

00:34:44.320 --> 00:34:46.100
People who don’t keep learning are missing out.   

00:34:46.400 --> 00:34:48.750
Even if we don’t grow financially,   

00:34:49.150 --> 00:34:53.280
with knowledge we’ll tend to 
  make better decisions.   

00:34:53.560 --> 00:34:56.760
And these five things are
 what made me who I am.   

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:01.660
Yes, my IQ is 148. My IQ is right there.  
 I’ve taken the test three times.   

00:35:01.660 --> 00:35:06.270
141, 142, 148. My TPA 
score is over 600.   

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:11.300
But that means nothing if it’s not 
put into real action.   

00:35:11.300 --> 00:35:15.460
I’d just be a smart person 
doing nothing.   

00:35:15.460 --> 00:35:19.340
That’s why I said to my father,  

00:35:19.340 --> 00:35:22.310
 If I don’t use social media
 for health education  

00:35:22.310 --> 00:35:23.800
in normal language   

00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:27.590
or to share my views 
 on education,   

00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:35.540
then people will keep thinking doctors are 
just like that—wearing white coats, strict.   

00:35:35.540 --> 00:35:38.360
They’ll think that 
 healthcare is expensive. 

00:35:38.670 --> 00:35:43.800
If my dad weren’t a professor,  
 I wouldn’t be like this, Sir.   

