When they return to UGM, 
they actually teach.   

01:07:52.950 --> 01:07:54.950
Just teach, then go back abroad.   

01:07:54.950 --> 01:07:58.000
People look up to them, “Wow, that’s cool!”   

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:00.570
And more people are getting 
motivated to go to Japan.   

01:08:00.570 --> 01:08:04.000
Japan’s a top destination, especially for
 cardiology and internal medicine.   

01:08:04.000 --> 01:08:06.770
My friends go to Japan because others 
before them went to Japan.   

01:08:06.770 --> 01:08:09.260
Others go to Europe because they followed 
people who studied in Europe.  

01:08:09.260 --> 01:08:11.480
“Why didn’t Tirta go?”
 Well, I missed the boat.   

01:08:11.480 --> 01:08:16.600
But one day, I still want to go. I still have
 a shot at getting a master’s.   

01:08:16.600 --> 01:08:19.950
And for me, education is never limited by age.  

01:08:20.620 --> 01:08:21.860
 It’ll never be limited by age.  

01:08:21.860 --> 01:08:25.170
 And I agree with you, Pak Gita, 
there’s no other option   

01:08:25.170 --> 01:08:26.880
but to send educators abroad.   

01:08:26.880 --> 01:08:30.150
I actually wanted to comment on this
 “But UGM’s not bad!”   

01:08:30.150 --> 01:08:31.480
True, it's not bad.  

01:08:31.880 --> 01:08:34.970
But most global innovators come from-

01:08:35.770 --> 01:08:39.730
- I really respect schools in Indonesia,   

01:08:40.150 --> 01:08:42.280
but if we’re looking at global rankings,   

01:08:42.970 --> 01:08:48.020
Indonesian universities are still ranked
 in the 200s and up.   

01:08:48.970 --> 01:08:54.000
If we really want to seek knowledge, we go to 
the top-ranking schools, right?   

01:08:54.200 --> 01:08:56.820
Not that we shouldn’t go to the 200s.   

01:08:56.820 --> 01:09:01.060
We can go there too, but we also need 
people to aim for the top-ranked ones.   

01:09:01.060 --> 01:09:06.110
That’s what we need to make part of 
the culture. Don’t think so narrowly,   

01:09:06.600 --> 01:09:09.480
like what we have in this country
 is already enough.   

01:09:09.480 --> 01:09:13.220
We need openness. Education, in my view, 

01:09:13.220 --> 01:09:15.820
needs to be deeply rooted in openness.   

01:09:16.550 --> 01:09:19.550
Without openness, we can’t innovate   

01:09:19.550 --> 01:09:23.230
or evolve into something or someone better.   

01:09:23.950 --> 01:09:29.120
And you’ve been successful as a student, 
successful as a doctor,   

01:09:29.120 --> 01:09:33.340
successful as an entrepreneur, 
and successful as a storyteller.   

01:09:33.720 --> 01:09:34.540
Right?   

01:09:35.080 --> 01:09:39.050
That shift from medicine to 
entrepreneurship is incredible.   

01:09:39.770 --> 01:09:43.630
Now I want to go back to the 
health dimension.  

01:09:44.560 --> 01:09:49.660
I want to talk about mental health issues.

01:09:50.320 --> 01:09:54.140
From what I’ve seen in Surgeon General’s Reports 
from developed countries,   

01:09:54.140 --> 01:10:00.400
the most worrying diseases nowadays 

01:10:00.400 --> 01:10:05.420
aren’t heart disease, diabetes, 
or stroke, but depression,   

01:10:06.840 --> 01:10:09.980
anxiety, even suicide.   

01:10:09.980 --> 01:10:12.800
Earlier we were chatting casually   

01:10:12.800 --> 01:10:16.320
about Jonathan Haidt’s book, 
&lt;i&gt;The Anxious Generation,&lt;/i&gt;

01:10:16.320 --> 01:10:21.980
where he puts forward the 
hypothesis or even theory that   

01:10:23.080 --> 01:10:26.750
this is linked to excessive online activity   

01:10:27.260 --> 01:10:32.490
and a lack of offline activity.   
What do you think about that, Tirta?   

01:10:32.490 --> 01:10:38.060
– When you mentioned Jonathan Haidt, 
that aligns with medical papers.   

01:10:38.300 --> 01:10:42.440
Yes, technology is like a double-edged sword.  

01:10:43.120 --> 01:10:47.070
The upside is, it can take us to the
 highest point of innovation.   

01:10:47.850 --> 01:10:52.600
But the downside is, it makes 
us spend more time 

01:10:52.600 --> 01:10:54.830
in the tech world than in our 
real surroundings.   

01:10:56.010 --> 01:11:01.740
That’s especially clear with our generation, 
and those younger than me.   

01:11:02.200 --> 01:11:05.920
Why is Gen Z more vocal about 
mental health issues?   

01:11:05.920 --> 01:11:12.520
Because most of their lives have already 
been exposed to tech,   

01:11:12.520 --> 01:11:15.720
they’re used to expressing 
themselves on social media.   

01:11:15.720 --> 01:11:19.104
The peak was during the 2020 pandemic. 

01:11:19.100 --> 01:11:21.888
Gen Z was in their productive years 
either in high school, college,

01:11:21.900 --> 01:11:23.600
or starting their careers.   

01:11:23.600 --> 01:11:27.320
That early Gen Z cohort, born 
around 1998 to the 2000s,   

01:11:27.320 --> 01:11:32.700
most of them in 2020 were in 
their 5th or 6th semester.   

01:11:33.440 --> 01:11:36.380
And just like that, everything got cut off. 
Online learning.

01:11:36.380 --> 01:11:40.140
led to a spike in their screen time,  

01:11:40.140 --> 01:11:46.270
 and that led to skyrocketing anxiety.   

01:11:46.270 --> 01:11:49.760
So this anxiety issue, it’s actually 
affecting two generations.  

01:11:49.760 --> 01:11:54.360
Here’s the plot twist, this is from WHO, there’s now a World Anxiety Day,  

01:11:54.890 --> 01:11:58.650
World Depression Day, even a 
World Mental Health Day.   

01:11:58.650 --> 01:12:04.860
WHO says the economic losses from 
mental health issues in companies  

01:12:04.860 --> 01:12:07.310
are massive trillions of dollars.   

01:12:07.310 --> 01:12:10.330
I forgot the exact number, but it’s 
easy to find from WHO.   

01:12:10.330 --> 01:12:18.830
The main causes are anxiety in two groups: 
those born in the ’70s–’90s,   

01:12:18.830 --> 01:12:22.860
and in Gen Z. Both are anxious, 
but about different things.   

01:12:23.240 --> 01:12:27.610
Gen X is anxious about future uncertainty,

01:12:27.610 --> 01:12:29.120
rising house prices.   

01:12:29.120 --> 01:12:32.160
Gen Z is anxious about their career path.   

01:12:33.600 --> 01:12:36.010
They’re worried, 
“What if I can’t ever buy a house?”  

01:12:36.240 --> 01:12:38.140
So their defense mechanisms are different.   

01:12:38.600 --> 01:12:45.120
Gen X tends to bottle things up.   

01:12:45.120 --> 01:12:49.690
Gen Z is more vocal, they express it on 
social media and are more open.   

01:12:50.060 --> 01:12:54.570
And what’s the outcome of anxiety? 
It lowers your quality of life.  

01:12:54.570 --> 01:12:59.500
Anxiety is heavily influenced by two hormones: 
cortisol and adrenaline.   

01:12:59.500 --> 01:13:05.500
When cortisol rises, it increases your
 risk of insulin resistance.   

01:13:05.500 --> 01:13:09.850
Because we’re anxious, our sympathetic nervous system 
stays on, we’re constantly in “ready” mode. 

01:13:10.080 --> 01:13:12.080
So our blood sugar goes up, 

01:13:12.080 --> 01:13:18.400
blood pressure goes up, which ultimately leads to 

01:13:18.400 --> 01:13:20.860
stroke and heart issues.   

01:13:21.790 --> 01:13:24.970
Gen X’s anxiety comes from work stress   

01:13:25.340 --> 01:13:30.190
high pressure, instability, the threat of 
getting fired, fights at home.   

01:13:31.070 --> 01:13:37.400
That’s why psychiatrists now mostly 
see either Gen X or Gen Z.   

01:13:37.400 --> 01:13:38.490
So what about millennials?   

01:13:38.670 --> 01:13:43.290
Now this is interesting. Millennials are the 
most rebellious, the most vocal.   

01:13:43.740 --> 01:13:48.170
Honestly, my generation is the 
most thoughtful   

01:13:48.170 --> 01:13:52.810
and the most stubborn. 
So they think they’re fine.   

01:13:52.810 --> 01:13:55.470
“Oh, whatever. It’s not a big deal.”   

01:13:55.470 --> 01:13:57.120
So now we have a generation saying,  

01:13:57.120 --> 01:14:00.600
“What’s your problem? So weak! I was raised…”   
Yup, that’s my generation. 

01:14:00.600 --> 01:14:04.760
I won’t deny it. That’s my generation because I’m
 like that too, I used to think others were weaker.   

01:14:04.760 --> 01:14:10.570
And now I get it, after hearing from 
my psychiatrist friends.   

01:14:10.880 --> 01:14:18.280
There are two types of people who confide in them: 
Gen X parents with grown kids, and Gen Z.   

01:14:18.940 --> 01:14:23.450
Gen Z’s anxiety comes from screen time.   

01:14:25.630 --> 01:14:28.840
So friends out there, this is your 
cue to check yourself   

01:14:29.420 --> 01:14:33.800
if you’re using an iPhone, go to settings,   

01:14:33.800 --> 01:14:36.540
check your screen time, and look at 
your top three most-used apps.  

01:14:37.610 --> 01:14:41.100
I actually tested this on Pak Sandiaga. 
We had a conversation just like this, Pak.  

01:14:41.950 --> 01:14:45.420
And guess what? 
His number one app was Zoom.   

01:14:46.270 --> 01:14:47.560
I got him. 

01:14:47.560 --> 01:14:48.810
 "Come on, Mr. Sandiaga."   

01:14:49.770 --> 01:14:53.680
How long was the Zoom? 
2 hours and 43 minutes.   

01:14:53.680 --> 01:14:58.380
So it turns out, at his age, he spends
 his time in meetings.   

01:14:59.360 --> 01:15:04.440
His life is meetings. Number two was
 WhatsApp. Three, finance.  

01:15:04.440 --> 01:15:07.680
I don’t even know what finance app. I didn’t want to check. 
Social media was only number four.   

01:15:07.680 --> 01:15:10.480
So all this time, it turns out Amin 
was handling the social media.   

01:15:11.500 --> 01:15:14.170
And we only found out 
yesterday on stage.

01:15:14.400 --> 01:15:19.290
So if someone’s top three screen time apps 
are social media, that's a red flag.   

01:15:19.290 --> 01:15:23.400
Because on social media,
 anyone can be anyone.  

01:15:23.760 --> 01:15:25.640
You can craft your persona.   

01:15:25.640 --> 01:15:28.496
But young people are still
 figuring out who they are, 

01:15:28.490 --> 01:15:31.904
so they end up thinking, 
“Success must look like that.”  

01:15:32.350 --> 01:15:33.200
Leads to anxiety.   

01:15:33.200 --> 01:15:39.500
So if you want to reduce anxiety, limit your
 screen time on social media.  

01:15:39.840 --> 01:15:43.530
And if it’s high, make sure it’s not social 
media that’s taking up most of it. 

01:15:43.530 --> 01:15:48.800
If the highest is Zoom or a WhatsApp group,
 that means it’s for work.   

01:15:48.800 --> 01:15:53.610
But if your top screen time is still social media,
 especially TikTok or short videos,   

01:15:53.610 --> 01:15:55.960
your attention span will go down.    

01:15:55.960 --> 01:16:01.880
This is a 2023 study for most young 
people, born between 1991 and 2010, 

01:16:01.880 --> 01:16:07.000
our attention span has
 dropped to 8 seconds.   

01:16:08.220 --> 01:16:12.250
So if a video doesn’t get its 
point across in 8 seconds   

01:16:12.670 --> 01:16:16.600
you’ve seen it, right, Pak Gita? Those Shorts
 or TikToks that pop up like:   

01:16:17.690 --> 01:16:23.280
“Breaking news! Kidney failure from coffee? 
Find out now!”   

01:16:23.280 --> 01:16:25.310
That hook has to hit in the first 9 seconds.    

01:16:25.310 --> 01:16:25.720
-That’s wild.    

01:16:25.720 --> 01:16:28.510
-And if those first 9 seconds aren’t interesting    

01:16:28.750 --> 01:16:29.840
-Scroll.
-Yes.

01:16:30.030 --> 01:16:31.930
Turns out there's research behind that.   

01:16:31.930 --> 01:16:35.240
Because of high screen time on social media,   

01:16:35.240 --> 01:16:40.940
young people’s attention span is
 now down to 6.7 seconds.

01:16:40.940 --> 01:16:44.620
So if Endgame doesn’t 
open with a hook like:   

01:16:44.990 --> 01:16:49.200
“Dr. Tirta! His life story in just... watch now!”   

01:16:49.630 --> 01:16:52.960
But I see that Endgame still gets high views.

01:16:53.470 --> 01:16:55.850
That gives me hope. 
