But if that can’t be achieved, it’s tough.   

01:37:28.330 --> 01:37:32.270
How can they operate here if our local 
talent doesn’t meet their needs?   

01:37:32.270 --> 01:37:34.920
So they set up a site here,
 but all the talent is from abroad.   

01:37:35.160 --> 01:37:36.510
That’s the worst-case scenario.  

01:37:36.840 --> 01:37:39.900
And in the end, we just can’t-

01:37:39.900 --> 01:37:46.650
-In principle, I actually support the 
Minister of Health’s approach.  

01:37:46.940 --> 01:37:47.580
-Okay.

01:37:47.820 --> 01:37:53.560
- Let’s say there’s a disease 
in Sumedang   

01:37:53.560 --> 01:37:57.210
that only a medical expert
 from Sudan can cure.

01:37:57.680 --> 01:38:02.480
We should be open to bringing 
that doctor here, right?  

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:09.200
As long as we don’t have the necessary
 expertise locally to treat the illness

01:38:09.200 --> 01:38:13.150
anywhere, not just Sumedang.   

01:38:13.150 --> 01:38:17.950
That concept should also apply in 
other contexts, like education.   

01:38:17.950 --> 01:38:25.390
If we want to train students in Tarakan 
to become physics experts,   

01:38:25.640 --> 01:38:30.090
and there’s no physics expert there,
 and none available in Jakarta either,  

01:38:30.090 --> 01:38:33.310
then we need to be open to bringing 
one in from anywhere.   

01:38:34.510 --> 01:38:36.680
That’s what we call the 
democratization of ideas.   

01:38:37.480 --> 01:38:42.590
And it’s a kind of pragmatism that’s
 very real in Singapore.   

01:38:42.990 --> 01:38:48.680
If they have a broken toilet, they ask, 

01:38:48.680 --> 01:38:54.320
“Who in the world can fix this efficiently?”

01:38:55.740 --> 01:39:00.670
And if nobody in Singapore 
can, they’ll hire

01:39:01.070 --> 01:39:06.280
a toilet expert from wherever, 
Norway, Ethiopia, Solo  

01:39:06.280 --> 01:39:08.830
as long as that person can 
be held accountable  

01:39:08.830 --> 01:39:10.830
as a real expert who can get 
the job done.   

01:39:11.960 --> 01:39:13.230
That’s openness.  

01:39:13.840 --> 01:39:18.510
- Exactly. That’s a point of view 
I’ve come around to.   

01:39:18.830 --> 01:39:20.650
I was resistant to it four years ago.  

01:39:21.680 --> 01:39:28.670
- As long as we understand that the
 long-term goal   is for these experts 

01:39:28.670 --> 01:39:31.660
to transfer their knowledge 
 to local people.  

01:39:31.660 --> 01:39:35.740
- So aside from hiring them,
 they also transfer knowledge.  

01:39:35.740 --> 01:39:38.520
The knowledge management aspect 
has to be clear, right? 

01:39:38.520 --> 01:39:48.110
Exactly. We can’t hide behind the blanket 
of nationalism without actually 

01:39:48.110 --> 01:39:52.030
curing the sick or educating 
the uneducated. 

01:39:53.850 --> 01:39:59.290
So there are two steps: we create a 
roadmap for knowledge management 

01:39:59.290 --> 01:40:03.770
or transfer; we recruit the 
best foreign talent   

01:40:03.770 --> 01:40:07.420
to temporarily fill the gap.   

01:40:07.980 --> 01:40:12.350
At the same time, these experts must agree 
to transfer their knowledge to us.   

01:40:12.400 --> 01:40:12.810
-Yes.

01:40:12.810 --> 01:40:17.150
- So when their contracts end, our local talent 
is ready, and the roadmap is implemented. 

01:40:17.150 --> 01:40:20.080
- Exactly. And once we’re ready,
 we can close the door.  

01:40:20.080 --> 01:40:24.380
- That’s the solution with the least risk.   

01:40:24.620 --> 01:40:27.720
- I used to be resistant too, Pak Gita. 
I totally agree now.  

01:40:29.020 --> 01:40:32.460
Back then I made decisions based 
purely on idealism.   

01:40:33.800 --> 01:40:36.480
Now I use fishbone analysis,
 Ishikawa diagram  

01:40:36.480 --> 01:40:38.810
to make decisions with the least risk.   

01:40:38.810 --> 01:40:40.810
And I think this has the least risk. 

01:40:41.930 --> 01:40:47.440
-Nationalism should manifest 
in national resilience.   

01:40:48.350 --> 01:40:52.890
And national resilience can 
only be sustained if we’re

01:40:53.340 --> 01:40:58.240
capable, healthy, educated, cultured,   

01:40:58.240 --> 01:41:05.340
civilized, communicative,  
and informed. 

01:41:05.340 --> 01:41:09.310
-So I’d revise my earlier opinion, 
foreign talent 

01:41:09.310 --> 01:41:13.440
isn’t just a worst-case scenario. It could 
actually be a big advantage for us. 

01:41:13.710 --> 01:41:18.030
- Absolutely. It’s empirical. I’ve seen 
it even in China.   

01:41:18.350 --> 01:41:20.430
How they're being open. 

01:41:20.430 --> 01:41:24.010
Back in 1978, Deng Xiaoping began reforms.   

01:41:24.320 --> 01:41:27.610
Part of that was welcoming foreign investors   

01:41:27.610 --> 01:41:32.830
with the goal of transferring technology.   

01:41:33.390 --> 01:41:35.180
-78?
-78.

01:41:35.180 --> 01:41:38.080
Mao Zedong had died just
 1–2 years before that,   

01:41:38.080 --> 01:41:41.920
then Deng took over and launched reforms.   

01:41:41.920 --> 01:41:45.790
That’s when China’s era of openness began.   

01:41:45.790 --> 01:41:50.680
Now they’ve achieved technological
 supremacy.   

01:41:50.680 --> 01:41:55.240
They spent the past 30 years
 learning from America, Japan, 

01:41:55.240 --> 01:41:58.490
Korea, Europe, and now the roles have reversed.

01:41:58.800 --> 01:42:03.320
- So Korea was the same? 
During the reforms in 1988–1992?   

01:42:03.320 --> 01:42:03.920
-Oh, yes.

01:42:04.270 --> 01:42:05.630
-Japan too, around 1976.

01:42:05.630 --> 01:42:07.950
- Under Park Chung-hee and others.   

01:42:07.950 --> 01:42:12.840
But I think it’s not easy to shift 
the mindset in Indonesia

01:42:12.840 --> 01:42:15.880
toward openness.   

01:42:15.880 --> 01:42:21.480
Still, I truly believe in the
 democratization of ideas.   

01:42:22.960 --> 01:42:28.490
If there are no ideas in a place, then open the 
doors and let those ideas come in

01:42:28.880 --> 01:42:29.560
from anywhere. 

01:42:29.560 --> 01:42:36.300
- This is really interesting. Maybe if my doctor
 friends heard it directly from you, 

01:42:38.480 --> 01:42:40.570
they’d instantly understand the point of view.   

01:42:41.240 --> 01:42:42.010
Seriously.   

01:42:42.010 --> 01:42:45.770
Because to be honest, Pak Gita, 
in healthcare services,

01:42:49.390 --> 01:42:53.720
it’s harder dealing with 30 medical
 specialists than 30 patients.   

01:42:54.030 --> 01:42:59.310
Because each specialist wants to be heard.   

01:43:00.280 --> 01:43:03.770
So I feel like instead of the Minister 
of Health explaining this,

01:43:03.770 --> 01:43:06.440
it’d be better if you told 
them directly.   

01:43:06.440 --> 01:43:10.080
It’s really compelling, and I do agree
 with the perspective.  

01:43:10.190 --> 01:43:12.650
I even spoke to some doctor
 friends about it.   

01:43:13.710 --> 01:43:16.920
They asked, 
“Are you pro-Minister of Health?” 

01:43:16.920 --> 01:43:20.190
It’s not about being pro or anti. 
Let me explain the POV.   

01:43:20.190 --> 01:43:22.730
The Minister is making policy from 
a managerial perspective.   

01:43:23.120 --> 01:43:27.790
Okay, he’s not a doctor. So we understand 
he views it from a management angle,

01:43:27.790 --> 01:43:31.870
and he was brought in to handle the
 health system. That’s clear.   

01:43:32.680 --> 01:43:38.160
As a healthcare practitioner, it just so happens
 that the BOD is in a managerial role. 

01:43:38.480 --> 01:43:40.670
The conflict lies in the pace of change. 

01:43:41.200 --> 01:43:45.130
You want gradual change, 
while they want it fast. 

01:43:46.220 --> 01:43:50.640
So what should be done? 
You have to meet halfway. 

01:43:51.310 --> 01:43:55.630
If both of them are in the BOD 
and you’re the executor, 

01:43:55.630 --> 01:43:57.290
and nobody wants to meet in 
the middle, it’s tough.

01:43:57.800 --> 01:44:03.600
Because change will inevitably 
happen, no matter what. 

01:44:04.680 --> 01:44:09.420
Now, the difficult part is, those who want 
to change are usually young doctors, 

01:44:10.250 --> 01:44:12.750
because they’re more open 
with my generation. 

01:44:12.750 --> 01:44:14.620
My generation is now becoming specialists.

01:44:14.620 --> 01:44:17.280
It’s only been 3 or 4 years, those
 I often invite to my podcast 

01:44:17.660 --> 01:44:21.480
that generation is now becoming 
specialists, and they’re more open. 

01:44:21.740 --> 01:44:25.080
-Yes. I saw the one with the urology expert. 

01:44:25.080 --> 01:44:28.910
-Yes, Dr. Wisda. When he educates,
 it’s very plot-twist-y. 

01:44:28.910 --> 01:44:31.424
He never forbids patients 
from doing anything. 

01:44:31.424 --> 01:44:33.050
He always says, “It’s okay, as long 
as it’s not excessive.” 

01:44:33.050 --> 01:44:34.990
That’s totally different from 
doctors in the old days. 

01:44:35.210 --> 01:44:37.980
Now, the doctors who are resistant, 
we can’t blame them either. 

01:44:37.980 --> 01:44:43.790
That’s why if the Minister wants this to go 
smoothly, he has to sit in the middle. 

01:44:43.790 --> 01:44:45.960
It’s a triangle of assets within a company. 

01:44:45.960 --> 01:44:51.260
So as policymakers, the Commission 9, the doctors,

01:44:51.500 --> 01:44:53.310
but they all have big egos. 

01:44:53.930 --> 01:44:56.240
Because no one wants to meet in
 the middle, well, this is the result.

01:44:56.240 --> 01:44:59.690
It’s like in a company let’s say you and I. 

01:45:00.280 --> 01:45:04.720
You hire a consultant, maybe McKinsey or PwC, 

01:45:04.720 --> 01:45:08.620
to make changes. I resist eventually, 
the company collapses. 

01:45:08.920 --> 01:45:13.310
And this keeps happening with BPJS. 
BPJS is already bleeding. 

01:45:13.310 --> 01:45:15.850
It just so happens the director
 used to be my former dean, 

01:45:16.030 --> 01:45:20.650
Mr. Gufron. So yeah, it keeps bleeding.
 If we keep bleeding, 

01:45:20.650 --> 01:45:24.030
it’s tough. Hospitals might not 
be able to pay their bills.

01:45:24.030 --> 01:45:26.280
That’s why this must be addressed immediately, 

01:45:26.280 --> 01:45:29.370
both from the BPJS side, meaning healthcare 
service financial management, 

01:45:29.370 --> 01:45:34.680
insurance, or in terms of talent management, 
and that’s a chicken-and-egg problem. 

01:45:34.680 --> 01:45:41.070
And what can we do? If we 
go back to startups,

01:45:41.070 --> 01:45:43.640
it turns out what my professor
 said was true. 

01:45:43.640 --> 01:45:47.720
Meritocracy is very difficult to 
implement here. Our culture 

01:45:47.720 --> 01:45:51.000
has always been to recruit people we trust, 
based on loyalty. What’s the term? 

01:45:51.000 --> 01:45:53.000
-Patronage and/or loyalty. 

01:45:53.310 --> 01:45:56.200
-Yes, patronage and loyalty. 
You're like a professor. 

01:45:56.200 --> 01:45:59.160
The last time I met Bu Yuni Ros, she said, 

01:45:59.160 --> 01:46:04.220
“Don’t ever, Tirta, recruit someone…” 
this is her actual quote. 

01:46:04.860 --> 01:46:08.830
“I get really upset when people recruit 
just because they’re friends. 

01:46:09.260 --> 01:46:11.420
A company once collapsed 
because of that.” 

01:46:11.420 --> 01:46:16.860
She ranted about it in class. And you 
are the second person who said that.

01:46:16.860 --> 01:46:19.400
Two of my teachers said the 
same thing so it must be true. 

01:46:19.400 --> 01:46:23.260
So the problem in Indonesian companies
 is hiring the wrong people, 

01:46:23.260 --> 01:46:26.700
setting age limits, and not creating 
a clear career path. 

01:46:26.700 --> 01:46:28.380
And when I joined Unilever, 

01:46:28.380 --> 01:46:31.530
I joined Unilever and United Tractors recently, 

01:46:31.630 --> 01:46:35.550
for the first time, as a consultant. 

01:46:36.250 --> 01:46:38.960
Their meritocracy is amazing, I admit. 

01:46:38.960 --> 01:46:41.790
At Unilever, the meritocracy is excellent. 

01:46:41.790 --> 01:46:45.790
And funnily enough, if we look at 
Unilever’s financial statement, 

01:46:45.980 --> 01:46:49.770
their biggest expense is for
 knowledge management. 

01:46:51.440 --> 01:46:53.980
-Knowledge management, research 
and development. 

01:46:53.980 --> 01:46:55.280
-Yes, their budget is massive for that. 

01:46:55.280 --> 01:46:58.400
They don’t hesitate to spend on those things. 

01:46:58.400 --> 01:47:01.500
And UT, United Tractors, also allocates 
budget for that. 

01:47:01.500 --> 01:47:07.520
That’s when I realized why these companies
 remain stable for 30 or 40 years. 

01:47:07.520 --> 01:47:09.870
Because their meritocracy is clear. 

01:47:09.870 --> 01:47:12.780
Maybe their salaries aren’t as big 
as tech startups, 

01:47:12.780 --> 01:47:18.380
but their career paths, knowledge structure,
 and recruitment process are all clear.

01:47:18.700 --> 01:47:22.680
That’s something we millennials 
need to work on. 

01:47:23.690 --> 01:47:25.760
Gen X turns out to not be 
so wrong after all. 

01:47:27.070 --> 01:47:30.430
Because we used to think Gen X was wrong.

01:47:31.120 --> 01:47:33.610
“Why are you so ambitious about your careers?” 

01:47:34.300 --> 01:47:36.730
Well, they’re the ones making 
the policies and it’s neat.

01:47:37.690 --> 01:47:41.000
And we’re too ambitious, trying to
 handle everything ourselves, 

01:47:41.000 --> 01:47:42.800
while the ones with solid networks 
are the baby boomers. 

01:47:43.470 --> 01:47:48.360
Turns out Gen X is actually the 
game-changer, in my opinion. 

01:47:48.360 --> 01:47:51.880
So people born in the ’70s to ’80s 

01:47:52.250 --> 01:47:55.150
are now the ones worthy of becoming leaders, 

01:47:55.450 --> 01:47:57.610
In my opinion. ’70s to ’80s. 

01:47:58.670 --> 01:48:01.870
The president is a baby boomer. 
The vice president is a millennial. 

01:48:02.640 --> 01:48:04.360
No Gen X in the top leadership yet. 

01:48:05.210 --> 01:48:06.220
-Let’s hope. 

01:48:06.560 --> 01:48:12.810
-I really hope that Gen X will be given 
the chance to lead 

01:48:13.390 --> 01:48:17.800
I think the meritocracy would be clearer, because 
they might be more capable of ensuring that. 

01:48:17.800 --> 01:48:21.280
From the five companies I’ve worked with, 

01:48:21.280 --> 01:48:24.110
most of their leaders are Gen X, 
and they are clear. 

01:48:24.480 --> 01:48:29.950
I don’t know why they manage to live frugally, 
their social media accounts are private 

01:48:32.800 --> 01:48:36.720
Gen X right now- 
I actually want to ask you,

01:48:36.720 --> 01:48:40.300
why aren’t Gen X leading yet? 

01:48:40.640 --> 01:48:42.440
Can I ask that? Is that okay? 

01:48:42.440 --> 01:48:46.750
-Of course. I just haven’t really thought about it. 

01:48:46.750 --> 01:48:49.230
-So those born in the ’70s are now what, 54?

01:48:49.230 --> 01:48:50.010
-In their 50s. 

01:48:50.010 --> 01:48:55.160
-Yeah. People born in the ’70s to ’80s 
should be in leadership now. 

01:48:55.400 --> 01:49:03.600
-But if they’re not that active on social media,
 that might actually be a positive trait. 

01:49:03.880 --> 01:49:06.400
-Yeah, they’re really low-profile. 

01:49:06.400 --> 01:49:12.490
-And if they’re firm about hiring based on
 meritocracy, that’s an incredible attribute. 

01:49:13.310 --> 01:49:17.390
That’s the kind of leader we’ll need going 
forward whether male or female 

01:49:17.920 --> 01:49:21.740
who firmly chooses based on meritocracy.

01:49:21.740 --> 01:49:28.350
Not just in government, but also in 
entrepreneurship, in academia, everywhere. 

01:49:29.390 --> 01:49:33.720
Right now, we’re in an era saturated with

01:49:33.720 --> 01:49:38.030
festivalization or sensationalism,
 lacking intellectualization. 

01:49:38.780 --> 01:49:43.000
That’s what should be prioritized. 
That’s why conversations like this 

01:49:43.000 --> 01:49:45.360
hopefully they’ll be part of the
 intellectualization process. 

01:49:45.360 --> 01:49:48.670
-This is valuable knowledge for me, honestly. 
I’ve learned so much. 

01:49:49.080 --> 01:49:53.020
In fact, I’m becoming more certain because
 my dream has shifted. 

01:49:53.660 --> 01:49:57.520
I haven’t told you about this yet.

01:49:57.900 --> 01:50:00.990
My ultimate goal now is to keep 
studying, I want to teach. 

01:50:00.990 --> 01:50:05.530
I’m currently at UGM. I’m helping out
 with public relations at UGM. 

01:50:05.530 --> 01:50:09.640
I’m also a guest lecturer at two campuses. 

01:50:10.250 --> 01:50:13.150
So it turns out I might have the privilege 
when it comes to income. 

01:50:13.150 --> 01:50:18.960
I know that lecturer salaries in Indonesia
 aren’t as good as in Finland or Germany, 

01:50:19.200 --> 01:50:22.920
but I have the privilege to share knowledge
 without worrying about income. 

01:50:22.920 --> 01:50:26.880
-You should think about how 
you can teach abroad too. 

01:50:26.880 --> 01:50:27.690
Guest lecture.

01:50:27.690 --> 01:50:29.760
-That’s hard.

01:50:29.760 --> 01:50:32.600
-No, because your storytelling is extraordinary. 

01:50:32.600 --> 01:50:36.160
You should be able to tell stories 
abroad about Indonesia. 

01:50:37.020 --> 01:50:39.630
That’s nationalism. 

01:50:39.630 --> 01:50:45.550
-I’ve never done it. Once I got the chance 
during undergrad, and I turned it down. 

01:50:45.550 --> 01:50:47.290
-Well, God willing, the opportunity
 will come again. 

01:50:47.290 --> 01:50:51.050
-That’s my biggest regret when I buried that dream. 
-It’ll come again. 

01:50:51.600 --> 01:50:53.310
Believe it. It’ll come. 

01:50:53.980 --> 01:50:59.280
Tirta, it’s been almost two hours. 
Any final messages for our friends? 

01:51:01.630 --> 01:51:04.040
My message... 

01:51:04.270 --> 01:51:07.200
-Here’s my message to my peers, okay?
 I always base it on age. 

01:51:07.450 --> 01:51:13.470
To those born between ’85 and ’95, 
who are now in the career-building phase, 

01:51:13.470 --> 01:51:17.520
I’m sure you either have a little
 child or are still child-free. 

01:51:18.380 --> 01:51:21.930
If you have money, use it for these two things: 

01:51:22.700 --> 01:51:27.180
The most important investments aren’t bank
 deposits. Those are important, sure. 

01:51:27.808 --> 01:51:33.370
Stocks are important too. But before buying gold, 
spend your money on knowledge and health. 

01:51:33.370 --> 01:51:35.260
In my opinion, these aren’t expenses.

01:51:35.260 --> 01:51:39.290
You’ll never regret spending 
money on those two. 

01:51:39.290 --> 01:51:43.310
Medical checkups, exercise, education, because 
you’ll reap the benefits 10 years from now. 

01:51:43.310 --> 01:51:47.660
Trust me, if you were born between 
’85 and ’95. That’s for you. 

01:51:48.220 --> 01:51:51.370
For my younger bros born after ’96. 

01:51:51.370 --> 01:51:55.280
Those born in ’96 or ’97 are in an awkward spot,
 too old for Gen Z, too young for millennials. 

01:51:55.280 --> 01:51:56.730
Be whatever you want. 

01:51:56.730 --> 01:52:01.120
But to the Gen Z folks younger 
than me, you’re smarter than me. 

01:52:01.530 --> 01:52:03.950
Honestly. You’re smarter than me. 

01:52:04.300 --> 01:52:07.660
At ITB, I met some of you who were 
more ambitious, had higher GPAs, 

01:52:07.660 --> 01:52:10.220
and better soft skills than I do. 

01:52:10.220 --> 01:52:15.240
You’re generally better at Orange,
 Tableau, Power BI than I am.

01:52:15.240 --> 01:52:18.400
Use technology for something meaningful. 

01:52:18.800 --> 01:52:22.860
Job-hopping is okay. So you're not
 loyal to one company. 

01:52:23.680 --> 01:52:26.780
But that doesn’t mean rigid 
systems are wrong. 

01:52:27.280 --> 01:52:28.380
This is for you: 

01:52:28.380 --> 01:52:34.350
Sometimes the rigid, fixed structures 
are what provide clarity. 

01:52:34.350 --> 01:52:39.020
If you keep changing, it’ll lead to 
instability later in life, say, at 35,

01:52:39.020 --> 01:52:41.630
and we’ll be too tired to keep 
changing as we get older. 

01:52:41.950 --> 01:52:44.250
So use tech for good. 

01:52:44.250 --> 01:52:46.810
And if you want to job-hop for 
experience, go ahead

01:52:46.810 --> 01:52:50.400
but eventually you’ll find a stable 
company to settle into. 

01:52:50.400 --> 01:52:54.540
Now, this is for my seniors, 
my older generation, Gen X. 

01:52:55.560 --> 01:53:00.090
You’re now probably in your 
50s, 45, 50, or 55. 

01:53:00.620 --> 01:53:04.620
Believe me, dreams don’t 
end with numbers. 

01:53:05.660 --> 01:53:08.250
So if you feel your career is stuck,

01:53:08.250 --> 01:53:14.720
 that you never made it to BOD, 
only got to senior manager 

01:53:14.720 --> 01:53:18.800
that’s okay. But remember, your life and 
death only happen once. 

01:53:18.800 --> 01:53:23.280
So I want to say this to
 those in their 50s 

01:53:23.280 --> 01:53:25.980
because I have team members
 in their 50s. 

01:53:26.490 --> 01:53:30.970
My driver. I got him to start
 running 6 kilometers. 

01:53:30.970 --> 01:53:32.540
